          In “At Least 6 Ways To Win With CSS”, Josh recounted the pain points of CSS which led to the creation of CSS Modules.

          Valid things that are difficult to do with CSS Modules.

          One of the main FORC — fear of removing CSS.

          When one of the UI components is not imported anymore, at that point, it’s easier to delete CSS.

          Ultimaetly, Josh stressed that with anything there is a tradeoff. “Good or better” is subjective — what’s the cost?

          In Josh’s experience, CSS Modules gave important value in a number of areas. Simpler class names and writing during authoring — only concerned with stuff that makes sense in your module. During Debugging, CSS Modules offered the benefits of immutabile CSS. Look at a class name, and know what it means, without any more context. Explicit mapping to DOM is easy to trace back to source of error.

          Refactoring is made better by the dependency tree. As soon as a module is disconnected, it can be deleted. D4

