  = partial("photoessays/components/talk", locals: { slug: "#{current_page.data.slug}/30", talk: 'Progressive image rendering', name: 'José M. Pérez', twitter: 'jmperezperez' } )
  .Content_row
    .Content_main
      .Article_content
        :markdown
          After a quick coffee break, José took us through some advanced image optimisation techniques and avoiding some common pitfalls.

          One of the commonly-used incorrect ways trying to hiding images is using display: none on content images, but the browser will still see the image tag and load the resource.

          Unlike the costs associated with some tecnical choices, there is no downside to optimising your images. The Picure element and srcset is one solution, but the markup and CSS is tightly coupled and keeping markup and CSS in sync is extra effort.

          Another good technique is Lazy loading, but this can be difficullt to get right. The IntersectionObserver API is one way to help determine when elements are on the scren and should be loaded, and by displaying blurry, low-file-size placeholders, it can give a better end user experience.

          Only 7% of images on the web are progressive.

